{
  "texts": [
    "A typical approach to measure science and technology interaction is based on the information of patent citing to non-patent literature (NPL), mainly research papers, and the majority of studies cited above use this NPL citation based index (Narin and Noma, 1985; Schmoch, 1997; Marx and Fuegi, 2020).",
    "However, there are some shortcomings regarding the measure of the linkage between science and innovation.",
    "First, it is well known that papers with a substantial volume of citations get more mentions in research papers (Mathew effect; Merton, 1973).",
    "Such bias with patent citations should be smaller, given that the patent citations are regulated by the patent system, such as disclosure obligations of relevant prior arts in US patent law.",
    "However, it has been found that disproportionally large number of citations are made to some specific patents (Kuhn et al., 2020) and the citation patterns could be geographically biased toward more concentration as compared to the patterns by textual similarity measures (Feng, 2020)."
  ]
}